messages.content: My friend said if I work as a miner at here, I don't need to make code, is this right?
I know it's silly question, but please let me know.

Hi woody,

Welcome!

I would say you do need to be able to program to compete on this subnet. 

We are solving open source automl so an understanding of AI + programming is required to do well.

Hi @wanderingweights (τ, τ), I have a question regarding the competition rules. During the tournament, if my submitted code is designed to pull and use additional Docker images from DockerHub (such as my own custom containers), is this allowed? I want to ensure this does not violate any competition policies.

Hola 

Right now yes, but if that gets abused we would stop this from being within scope immediately and force everyone to use the same base docker. 

The idea is that the code is open source, so the docker image you start from should also have it's code open-source. 

We want to be flexible which is why we're open atm, but we will patch this straight away if we notice any abuse - before the tourn even finishes so no emission will flow to solutions that attempt this. 

Hope it helps!
Hello. I'd like to join this subnet. Do I need to skate at least $8,000 (to get into the top 32) to get started?

Hi!

Nope, we've recently incresed (from 16 to 32) so the stake requirements are reduced. Actually the last text competition, everyone that wanted to join could (zero stakers could even play). Whilst we don't expect that to continue, we are pushing for a much more moderate amount of stake to be needed. If I were to guess, $300 should do it this next comp set - but this is a complete guess. 

We're also working on shifting the set-up to be pay-to-validate, which miners pay the validation costs (approx $100) rather than staking - but thats a few weeks away from being added in.

Thanks for reply,
I thought bittensor is powerful because wide range of participants submit variants to improve, but cost barrier turns bittensor back to centralized tranning method.
I wish entry barrier is affordable to most devs and we could get daily incentives.

Couldn't agree with you more on the idea of having anyone able to compete if they have the skills, but there are costs to know which miners solution is best  and then to serve  solutions to customers - in legacy, miners need to run their own hardware continuously which costs a lot more than this.  

My personal two-cents is that $100s to cover the compute costs to compete for a prize of many tens of thousands is pretty reasonable and demonstrates motivation on the miners side.
Hi, @wanderingweights (τ, τ) tour miners are getting 5% alpha after finished?
After what's finished sorry snr?

If you mean right now? No, they have 50% available (split text and image) with 5% of this burned + given to legacy miners (2.5%) for every 1% difference they are from historic legacy miner results - up to 77.5%. 

Basically the closer tourn miners get to historic results the more emission flows to them. The very worst case will be 11.25% emission as a minimal to tourn miners. 

Everything rests on getting performance parity. The game isn't just to win the tourn, but to beat/match legacy miner results 🤙 

Follow the constants in this section to see how this works in the code
https://github.com/rayonlabs/G.O.D/blob/99228baf1872670700bf121f5541ead15e3e9ab1/validator/core/constants.py#L283

Hope it helps!

Hola hola - If you’re running the exact same code then there’s a chance that the same training parameter and seeds result in the same exact same loss (especially since all miners run on the same hardware reducing any non-determinism). This will still be marked as a duplicate, it’s not in keeping with the idea of the subnet and tourn. We don’t want to be evaluating the exact same repo many times. Duplicate in this case isn’t about the hash but the actually loss outputs (if you send me the task id I’ll confirm this for you tomorrow when I’m back home).

Hope it helps!

Hi everyone, I have a quick technical question: how often are new miners picked up for pings/evaluations, and roughly how many miners are usually involved in each tournament? I couldn’t find this info here or on GitHub. Thanks a lot to anyone who can share some insights 🙏

Heyo, if you're only talking about the tournament system then miners are sent the /training_repo/ request once every couple days (24 hours after the end of either a text or image tournament) and as of right now there are 32 miners in each tournament 🙂 though that number may change in the next couple weeks

Thanks Phoenix for the explanation earlier about the 1–2 days. I have had a miner online on Sub-56 for 5 days now and I’m still waiting for the first ping. Before I stop it to fine-tune the model with the official dataset, I’d like to understand if that first ping is essential to be “censused” and included in the tournament cycle. Should I wait to receive it before making modifications, or even if I were offline at that moment would I still be included in later cycles?
Are you only planning on participating in the tournaments or closed source as well?

If only the tournaments then your miner server only needs be available when 24 hours after a tournament ends to receive the /training_repo/ request then you'll be added to the tournament (and the tournament will use whatever repo is referenced at the time of this request)
And unless you are the winner the server needs to be active every tournament at the time of the /training_repo/ request to be included
Finally in order to get the request make sure you meet the minimum stake requirements (this will be changed in the next few weeks)
Currently for text tournaments it looks like the lowest miner to get in had 125 alpha staked, so make sure you have at least that to get a request 🙂

Ok, I understand: to participate it takes around 125 α = about 5 TAO. I didn’t expect the minimum stake requirement to be that high, since in the metagraph I can see miners with lower stake that are still active. I’ll go ahead and update my miner now, thanks a lot for the info.

It depends on the tournament type and the actual number is hard to know before hand, for the image tournament I see miners with only 5 alpha staked, but its worth it to have higher stake to ensure you get in and you can always withdraw your stake later 🙂 good luck!

Things are looking spicy on the tournament side. 

On both sides the burn is being reduced huge amounts since the performance of open-source is so close to parity now. 

To make things fairer after a bit of testing we'll have in: 

https://github.com/rayonlabs/G.O.D/tree/separated_burn

Currently the burn is calculated and distributed based on combined text and image performance. To above PR will separate this out. So if the image tourn gets much close than text or vice versa to the legacy performance then they will be rewarded proportionally rather than the average of the two. The burn emission back to legacy is calculated in the same way, if there is more burn due to poor performance on text, then legacy will stand to gain only on the text side and not the image. 

The core reason is to have a fair distribution based on performance - any questions, fire them at us. 

The other change is that chat type problems have been added to the text tourn so repos will need to support this going forward. We won't add them to the final to be fair to the current champs but as soon as we get a new champ or the threshold becomes 5% we will add this task type to the final.

Hi, I have a question regarding the real-time serving cycle. I’ve checked the official docs but I couldn’t find these details.
Could you please clarify how the full process works:
– From when a miner first registers (with 0 stake),
– To how/when the first job is assigned and how new miners are rotated in,
– Which model is actually used for real-time jobs, and the corresponding GPU/VRAM requirements,
– And finally whether there is any minimum stake needed to be included in the cycle.

Basically: what does the real-time cycle look like from job assignment, to model execution, to when the miner exits the job? Thanks a lot 🙏.

Hi @bob1962 

So the 0 stake is fine for real-time, all miners are offered regardless. 

Then as jobs come in from customers (and some synthetic) they are offered to miners to train. 

Up to about 8 miners are offered each job and they compete with each other to produce the best model which the validator compares performance based on an unseen test-set. 

The miner exits the job when they like, but there is a time-limit to a job so the validator will ask the miner for their model at this time, so the miner need to have it ready and uploaded to huggingface at that point. 


There are compute requirement ideas here https://github.com/rayonlabs/G.O.D/blob/main/docs/compute.md  but for real-time, we can't say for sure what current top miners run. 

https://github.com/rayonlabs/G.O.D/blob/main/docs/miner_advice.md << some extra nuggets to get you going here 🤙
Only addition to this is that the bar for real-time survival is high, you need to win your first job with a hotkey to stay alive. If you lose, you'll need to re-reg and try again.

**Hi peeps,**

📢 **Important GRPO Updates** - A couple of key changes to improve system integrity:

---

🔧 **GRPO Evaluation Improvements**

We've identified and addressed an issue where some participants were **overfitting their fine-tuned models to the reward functions**, causing models to drift too far from their original base models.

To mitigate this behavior, we've **increased the KL divergence regularization component** in our GRPO evaluation system. This will help ensure models maintain better alignment with their base models while still allowing for meaningful improvements.

---

🏆 **Tournament Update - New Comparison Method**

We're **temporarily removing GRPO tasks from text tournament final rounds**, but with a clear path back:

**The Issue:**
- Tournament finals previously compared performance against **historic GRPO tasks from legacy**
- With our new KL divergence updates, **metrics are now different** and not directly comparable
- We can't re-evaluate previous GRPO tasks since some models have **missing HuggingFace repositories**

**The Solution:**
- We're **moving away from legacy comparisons** and will start **comparing current tournament winners with previous tournament winners**
- This new approach will allow us to **re-include GRPO tasks back into tournament final rounds** once implemented

This ensures fair competition while we transition to a more sustainable evaluation system that doesn't rely on legacy data.

---

These changes strengthen the integrity of our evaluation system and ensure fair competition for all participants. Thanks for your understanding as we continue to improve the network! 🤙

---

More updates coming soon - stay tuned! 🚀
